{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_klamath_ver01/data/sn85066387/00175046628/1910071501/0345.xml":{"full_text":"VOLUME CVIIL\u2014 XO. 45.\nFLANNERY BACK\nIN POLITICS ON\nBARBARY COAST\nEnters Tenderloin Fight for As\nsemblyman Charlie Lightner,\nAdvocate of \"Reform\"\nLatters Associates on Machine\nSiate Too Raw for Even\nBudgey Nelson to Swallow\nGEORGE A. VAN SMITH\nThat Harry I\\ Flannery\"* ambition to\n.be a gr^at political power \"was not\nWholly satisfied by his brief if highly\nFpeetacular occupancy of tho presidency\nof the police commission is indicated by\ndevelopments in the forty-fifth assem\nbly district. From the Barbary coast\nmonies the cheering- intelligence that the\nsometime autocrat of the police depart\nment is in the game again as chief\nbacker of Assemblyman Charlie Lfght\nn*r. who aspires to democratic zionii\nliation and reelection.\nLightner was put over in the forty\nfifth two years agro by a combination of\n\\u2666\u2022ircumstancs in which the reformers,\ndemocrats and republicans alike, and\nIhe nomination of lk>uis Parents by the\nrepublican machine figured most promi\nnently. Flannery's hand did not show\nin the election rf Lightner, but it ap\npeared on the collar of the reform leg\nislator immediately after he took his\nseat at Sacramento.\nWHECLAX OUT\nFlannery's acknowledged legislative\nprize package was Al Wheelman, whom\nFlannery subsequently attempted to\nmake a judge and whose connection\nwith the little diversion which called\nthe attention of the Marin county\nirrar.d jury to Flannery was a more re\ncent mark of distinction. Wheelan has\nbeen located .*ince the Marin county\nunpleasantness. but it is understood\n\u2022That he is considered unavailable as\n\\u25a0 legislative timber. Wheelan promptly\niifsumed the guardianship of Reformer\nL,sghtner and collectively they unloaded\na bunch of cinch bills raw enough to\noishearten Grove L. Johnson. The\ndemocratic reformers who were rlgsred\ninto selecting Lightner yelled for help\n\\u25a0 and swore \"never more\" Lightner for\nUifm. Through circumstances over\n-which hf could not be expected to exer-\nlre control Flannery has been forced\n'\u2022to\" dispense with Wheelan as a candi\n.idate, .but Lightner remains to him.\n'..I? may be that Flannery is down on\n,-Uightner. who has no opposition for the\ndemocratic nomination, merely as an\n\\u25a0: accident insurance policy to cover a\nlegislative situation that would put Abe\nTCuef to the blush and that has driven\nBudgey Nelson into the realm of re\nform politics.\nOEMvtiRI OS M.VTE\nThe Finn-Lynch slate for the forty\nfifth Jistrict carries tbe name of D. M.\nDenegri for republican nomination to\nthe assembly. Denegri is the chosen fa\nvorite of Jim Grffin, the North beach\npolitician, whose legalized interest in\nthe Johnson-Jeffries mill was demon\netized by Governor Gillett.\nNor la Griffin the most prominent of\nI\u00bbenegri's supporters and sponsors. Joe\nBarbetta and \"Butch\" Geggus known\nto police fame as promoters of certain\n\\u25a0 harmless gani\u00bbs* for the edification and\nfinancial enlightment of suckers and as\nthe financiers behind several Comraer\n\\u25a0 clal street leases are for Denegri.\nTommy Dwyer cuvs in with his friend\nand partner. Griffin. Then there are\nLouis Strbhl and I..ouis Parente. Strohl\nwas a legislator once upon a time.\nWhen not engaged in the business of\nstatecraft, he did politics and signed\nthe payroll on the water front. Most\n-of those things he does yet. and some\nof tHem he did so well that he was\nenabled to associate himself with\nParente in the promotion of a craps\ngame, subsequent to the last munici\npal election. \"Old Faithful\" Ed Buckley\nis there, too. for DenegrL but Buckley\nis not an active businessman and only\nfigures In tl>e second flight of rare*\nbirds behind the machine candidate.\nNELSON TURN'S REFOHMKR\nThe Denepri flash was so raw that\n\\u25a0\u2022 Budgey Nelson, who had always gone\nthe route with never a murmur, threw\nUp his hands and refused to partici\npate. Then he went that one better by\n\\u25a0 getting ir.to the fight for L. G. Briz\nzolara. who stand* to get the primary\nvotes of the republicans who have\n\"never been on the \"small book\" and\nthe reform democrats of the district.\nNelson has always been a power in the\ndistrict. The combination against him\nis almost *as stiff as it is fragrant, but\nthat he has a chance of beating it is\n\\u25a0 considered one of the reasons for the\nreappearance of Flannery as sponsor\nfor Lightner.\nThe situation in the twenty-second\ndistrict, including the thirty\nninth and fortieth assemblj- dostrlcts.\npresents some well defined earmarks of\nthat double cross of which machine\nmanipulator* are frequently accused\nnnd infrequently convicted. Assembly\nman Callan, the. Lincoln-Roosevelt\nleague candidate for the senate, is op\nposed by Jack Cassidy of the United\nn\u00bbilroads forces; Edgar Levey, a young\nattorney who was formerly a member\n\"of iDstrict Attorney Langdon's office\nstaff, and Edwin T. Murray, who got\nBway with a reformer, pose in the thir\nty-ninth for several years.\nMfMIRRAV MAY AVIV\nCashidy has been consistently de\nscribed as a \"butter in\" and unwelcome.\nfjevmy was declared impossible, because\nJie had been a member of Langdon's\n\u2022official family, although only a bond\nand warrant clerk. McMurray undoubt\nedly has the support of Kome of the\nconservatives in the thirty-ninth who\nhave not been machinrmen and. \"with\nthe machine's support and Cassidy out\ncf the way reasonably could be expected\nto w!n. It was given out that Finn had\nagreed to accept the erstwhile reformer\n\u00abnd that the combine was to go down\nthe line for McMurray.\nSome of the strongest and cleanest of\nthe machine men in the fortieth whis\npered it around that McMurray -looked\ngood/ After the conference devoted to\nthe selection of the combine's slate the\nFignal was hung out for \"McMurray all\nthe way\" on ojie side of the cab. ami\nLevey was notified that he was the\nfair hairej one from the other side.\nBoth signals may be good for some\ngeneral purposes, but if McMurray has\nnot been, given the hook by his new\nfriends thy are playing an unusually\nsubtle game.\nOn Wednesday night the machine re\npublican club of the thirty-ninth dis\ntrict whooped it up' for Davison f6r\ncongress and formally indorsed Levey\nfor senator and Julius Frankel, the\ncombi\u00dfp's assembly candidate for the\nlower house. I^ast night the union .labor\ncounty committeemen of the same dis\ntrict performed a. like, service for Levey\nand Franke.l. and included In their.'ln\ndorsement'lisl Aldcn Anderson for.gov-;\nCharles Luhmann,\nAged Seven, Who\nVanished July 3\nfrnor.C W. Davison for congress, W.\nH. Bemlss for clerk of, the supreme\ncourt and C. D. Dorn for justice of the\npeace.- \u2022\\u25a0\n3IcCARTH V BETS $100 \\u25a0\nFrank Daroux, the book -.maker, p:ot\naction for $10,000 yesterday by. betting\nIt against $100 that Ellery I would not\nbe nominated for governor. s The short\nend of the bet was taken by Jack Mc-\nCarthy for a syndicate composed* of em\nployes of the state engineer's office.\nMcCarthy did not disclose the number\nof contributors to the $100\" syndicate,\nbut he did declare that not all of the\n$50 that he bet against '$5,000 on\n\"Wednesday was his own. That Mc-\nCarthy was satisfied with the odds\ngiven him by Daroux was evidenced\nyesterday by his formal refusal to ac\ncept any commission j for his trouble\nIn collecting- money for the book maker.\nOn Wednesday,\" after laying $5,000\nagainst McCarthy's $50, Daroux told\nEllery's manager that after winning\nhis bet he would give him ?25 commis\nsion for securing what Daroux consid\nered a gift of $50.\nMcCarthy's efforts to .break Daroux\nby accepting stray bits of his 100 to 1\nodds against Ellery, constitute all or\nthe short end acceptances.. Daroux's\n5 to 1 offer against Anderson goes with\nout takers.\nBKATTV INDORSED\nHenry X. Beatty,' one of the best as\nsemblymen San Francisco ever- elected,\nand Daniel P. Regan, who will try con\nclusions with Dan Toomey for nomina\ntion to the senate from the eighteenth\ndistrict, were unanimously indorsed on\nWednesday night by a mass meeting of\nthirty -sixth district republicans.\nPolitics gave place to a smoker and\nentertainment last Wednesday evening,\nwhen the members of the Alden Ander\nson club of the forty- first assembly dis\ntrict met in Golden Valley hall at La\nguna and Union streets. Among the\nspeakers were Nat Coghlan, Robert B.\nClark, Thomas Sweeney, W.E. Davis,\nThomas Tracy, C. E. Thurston. and\nThomas Barton.\nHustling Necessary\n[Special Diipaich to The Call]\nSACRAMENTO, July 14.\u2014 The belief\nwas expressed at the secretary of\nstate's office today that the probability\nwas- that more than one aspirant for\nnomination for the senate and assem\nbly would be left out because of the\ninability to have their petitions at the\noffice on Saturday, July 16, the last day\nof filing. Particularly will this be true\nof remote counties.\nAnother obstacle will be reached in\nfiling the fees with the secretary of\nstate, as many of these fees have been\nturned over to the county treasurers.\nThe affected counties in which one or\nmore assembly 'districts are composed\nare:\nHumboldt, Mendoclno. Butte, Nevada,\nSonoma. N'apa, Yolo, Sacramento. So\nlano, Marin, Contra Costa, San Joaquin,\nSan Francisco, Santa Cruz, Alameda,\nSan Mateo,\" Santa. Clara, San Benito,\nMonterey, Fresno, Kings,' San Luis\nObispo. Santa Barbara, -Ventura, Kern,\nLos Angeles, San Bernardino, Orange,\nRiverside, San Diego and Imperial.\n$500 FOUN D WHILE\nRAKING IN GARDEN\nBill Sticks in Tines of Garden\ning Implement\nA dilapidated $500 bill stuck on the\n\u00abnd of one of the tines of her garden\nraite was the reward reaped by Mrs.\nMary Wagner of Earlham, la., for rak\ning her yard one. day recently.\nShe noticed an old. piece of paper had\ngotten. stuck on .one. of the tines of the\nrake in; such a peculiar\". manner. 7 that\nshe. could not remove it without using\nher hands, says the Chicago Inter\nOcean. While unloosening the faded\npaper she noticed that its -size was \"the\nsame as a banknote. Investigating\ncloser, she detected the\" fainf outlines\nof engraving on the facie of the. paper.\nThe next day she presented. the paper\nto the Citizens' national bank, where a\nmicroscopic examination, showed it to\nbe \"a 'ssoo 'bill In a badly; decayed con\ndition. Upon being sent to the-treas\nury department at Washington, hovv- 1\niever, it was pronounced genuine and\nwas replaced with a* new $500 note. -_\nFive hundred dollar bills are not plen\ntiful around Earlham.. and although the\nfind has been advertised no claimants\nhave appeared. v\nBARRIES IDEAS COME!\nBY TOBACCO OUNCES\nNoted Writer Said. to. Gauge His\nWork by Pipe\nJ.. M. Barries passion for to.qacco. ls\nwell known and it is not surprising\nthat he gauges, his work by -his- pipe\nwhether he writes paragraphs, a leader\nor. a novel. Writing for,; a .newspaper\nhe secures an idea after- four .pipes,\nsays the .Boston. Herald. A chapter of\na novel is the result of 14' ouiTces.= And\nothers can not-write without, thinking,\nor- think before writing,, if [they Vare\nsmoking. Charles Lamb summed it all\nup in his \"Farewell, to\". Tobacco.\".\nFilth of the -mouth and tog ot the\nmind:\nAfrica,- that brags her foyson,\nBreede no sucjv prodigious .poison!\nHenbane, nightshade, both' together,-\nHemlock, aconite\nNay rather, .'.'\\u25a0.\nPlant divine, of rarest virtue!\nBlisters on the tongue would* hurt you!\nTwas but in-a'.sort I. blamed thee;\nNone e'er prospered who defamed thee.\nASPARAGUS CUREAIDS 5\nFARMER AND PATIENT\nI The 'Swiss,' so* a Paris- con temporary\nsays',,inv\u20acnt'all kinds of cures. to attract\n'\\u25a0 visitors to their beautiful country. Just\nnow\\it is tbe asparagus ciife.in Valais.\nThanks to alluvium,.' there^is^an abun\ndance 1 of, asparagus; in; the land in. the\nRhone valley, and tons are .exported to\nvarious countries' of Europe. The curen\nbepln at.theend of May, ranflffor about\na fortnight- the patients make aspara\ngus' their principal diet! 3 MLeat is rigor\nously banished/ It is claimed- that' this\nvegetarian diet is a most, effective\ncleanser of the gy\u00abteni. and, moreover.'\nthe cure has. cheapness to recommend it;\nRiacon parlor. No.-72.iN. S.G.'w.r will\nhold their pfcnlc Sunday, July 17th,\nFairfax Park. \\u25a0. \\u25a0 \\u25a04i-.'-;*Si\nTMEv dtS-MteE,\nMISSING BOY IS\nSOUGHT IN VAIN\nPolice Unable to Find Any Trace\nof Lad Who Disappeared\nTwo Weeks Ago\nLad Drops Out of Sight Follow\ning Dismissal of Sunday\nSchool Class\nCharlie Luhmann, the 7 year old son\nof Charles Lulimann of 1597 Treat ave\nnue, who\" disappeared following the\ndismissal of the St. Anthony Sunday\nschool class July 3, is still missing.\nFor a week and a half the. policeof\nthe bay counties have been trying to\nclear up the mystery, but the published\ndescriptions of the boy have brought\nno-return. Daily the grieving mother\nvisits the police station asking for\nnews of her little son.\nCharles L.uhmann, the father, \\u25a0 says\nthe boy was extremely fond of horses.\nOnce before he was missing. for two\ndays and then was found in the hay\nloft of a barn, where he had remained\nto be vnear the horses. Another time\nhe was klcked-ny a horse when lie in\nsisted on'stroking the animal. _.\nThe father says the boy is a sturdy\nfellow, who has the courage 'to, solicit\nhelp- if hungry or in need. His faith is,\nhowever, becoming shaken as the days\npass without word being, received.\nCharlie, attended the Sunday school\nclass with his\" sister Frances, who is\ntwo years older. He! was dressed in\ncorduroy knee breeches, brown blouse\nwith white stripes and/greeh cap. He\nhas very light hair, closely cropped;\nblue eyes and a round, bold face.\nMINING MAN INSOLVENT;\nLIABILITIES $149,446.74\nHenry F. Pierce Files Petition\nin Bankruptcy\n,-Henry F. Pierce; of San Francisco,\ninterested in mining projects and for\nmerly an asparagus grower on an isl\nand in the San Joaquin river near\nStockton, filed a petition in bankruptcy\nyesterday. His liabilities\" are scheduled,\nat 1149,446.74, with no assets. Accord\ning to the petition Pierce owes $25,\n679.34 on secured notes; $95,598.80 on\nunsecured notes, and 520,745.32 on ac\ncommodation paper, consisting of notes\nand bills.. The money is owed to the\nStockton savings bank, various mer\nchants In Stockton and two eastern\nparties.\nThe bank is secured by 100,000 shares\nof stock in' the Comstock-.lode mining\ncompany. His life is insured for $10,\n000, but this is not scheduled as an\navailable asset.\nPierces financial difficulties com\nmenced a year ago last winter. \\u25a0 At that\ntime he had heavy investments in. as\nparagus growing on an island in the\nSan Joaquin river. The high water of\nthat winter destroyed his crops and he\nhas been unable. to regain his financial\nstanding.\n~*M. J. Thomson, a farmer near Salinas,\nMonterey county, filed a petition in\nbankruptcy yesterday in the United\nStates district court. His liabilities are\nscheduled at $2,534.98, with $800 in\navailable assets.\nCOUPLE OFF TO FACE\nMINE ROBBERY CHARGE\nSheriff Takes Jones and Nie\nmyer to. Oroville \\u25a0\nJ. X. Jones, president, of the Madeline\nMeadows -irrigation 'company, and John\nNlemeyer, ah advertising solicitor, \"ar\nrested on Wednesday on a charge of\nstealing $1,000 worth of. gold from the\nSouthern Cross mine, near Oroville,\nowned by J. L.. Rosenthal. shoe mer\nchant of this city, were turned over to\nSheriff J. M. Chubbuk. He left with\nthem -for Orovilie. yesterday afternoon.\nJones said lie never saw the mine.\nNiemeyer wanted him to buy it, he de\nclared, and he sent an engineer to in-\nvestigate. who 1 reported -that it was not\nworth $60,000, the price Rosenthal\nasked for j it. That was all he I knew\nabout It. Niemeyer said his only in\nterest in themine Iwas- to promote. its\nsale and get ~a commission. When\nJones refused to buy. it he dropped :it.\nThe two other, 'men, ,W. H. Shewan\nand -J.-'H. Kennedy, who were arrested\nin ;Reno in [connection with the same,\noffense, have been arraigned in Oro\nville. j'~ \\u25a0\u2022\"i\nEUREKA VALLEY CLUB\nSECURES IMPROVEMENTS\nEighteenth Street Widened by\nWorks Board\n'Through tlie\":' 'campaign for good\nroads waged by the Eureka .Valley im\nprovement association work.is now be^\ning done by the board of \"public works\nin Eighteenth street, from Sanchez to\nCastro, a three -foot cut being made; on\neach side, widening the thoroughfare\nsix feet. \\u25a0''\\u25a0' \\u25a0.;-. .\\u25a0;',\"'.\n:The repaying- 'of 'the- same street\nfrom Sanchez to Castro, is also -being\nrushed, \"and w;ill be finished in] a short\ntime, and the Eureka association in-\nduced the -city, officials to, order- this\nwork \"also.\n.The; question of lightingr Market\nBtreet-from Valencia to Castro is. now\noccupying the. attention of the club, j\nand action' is expected -in -this -matter i\nshortly. Much complaint on this -sub\nject is heard .from (property ovrners\nalong the street v\nThis Space Reserved\nCalifornia Credit\nClothing Co.\nFAIRS FOLLOWED\nBY PROSPERITY\nCities \\Vhich Have Held Recent\nExpositions Tell of Pros* \\u0084\nperous Times I\nSan Francisco Committee About\nReady to Inaugurate Pub\nlicity Campaign\nThe few San Franciscans or CaHfor\nnians whose visions of happiness dur\ning the period of the: 1915 world's fair\nare clouded by. the /ear of business\ndepression immediately afterward will\nhave their doubts dispelled by the facts\nand' figures- which\" the -publicity com\nmittee. of the exposition company -is\ncollecting.\n-Requests have been pent to- \"prac\ntically all- of. the cities; that have held\nworld's fairs during: the last quarter of\na\" ..century, seeking information on\nbusiness conditions \"before. and after.:;\nG. W. Wattles, president .\\u25a0 of the\nOmaha and CouSicil Bluffs -street rail\nway company, who* was president of\nthe trans-Mississippi international ex\nposition at- Omaha'- in] 189S, has written\nthat the exposition 'was the beginning\nof, an epoch\" of unparalleled prosperity.\nFrom 1893 to 1898, he. wrote,. Omaha\nconditions had been* execrable, owing\nto 'the failure of crops and the free\nsilver ;craze. The exposition, he said,\nchanged conditions, brought new life\nthe city and, new; business. The fair\nwas followed by a steady and sub\nstantial\" progress.\" .Stock holders re\nceived back 92 l ,i per cent of the sub\nscriptions.\nI Seattle' also has experienced better\ncommercial conditions since the closing\nof the Alaska-Yukon fair. According\nto^ figures submitted by the Seattle\nchamber of commerce, bank clearings\nduring December, 190i>, showed an: in\ncrease of more than $14,000,000 over\nthe corresponding month of 1908.\nRealty: sales almost doubled and the\npopulations became substantially aug\nmented.\nToday, according to this report, the\nwholesale and jobbing companies\"are\ndoing a business which increases 10\nper cent: month by month. New hotels\nand apartmterits are now housing, many\nof the later arrivals.'thus keeping the\nbusiness of the old hotels practically\nat par. All, however, report better\nconditions than existed prior to the\nfair. r -\\u25a0-. .\\u25a0 r. \\u25a0i \\u25a0\n\"The Chicago .chamber of commerce\nreported no decrease in business, de\nspite, the fact; that the panic of IS93'\nprevailed during the\" progress ,of the\nfair. Clearing .house reports, realty\nsales, statistics: of building permits all\nshow- Chicago- slowly forging ahead\nduringrthe,\" few tumultuous years in\nwhich.t he.f ull- effect.o f the great panic\nwas felt. The fact that there was\nactually no business depression in the\nface of this panic is laid to some ex-,\ntent to the beneficial effects of the\nWorld's fair.\nThe 